of data science on the web.

00:08:32.479 --> 00:08:34.599
And the two primary technologies

00:08:34.599 --> 00:08:37.119
that we'll be talking about is,

00:08:37.119 --> 00:08:39.280
or we'll be talking about several technologies,

00:08:39.280 --> 00:08:44.280
but these are brought to you thanks to WebR and Pyodide.

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:46.440
But before we talk about them,

00:08:46.440 --> 00:08:50.280
let's talk about another tool called WebAssembly.

00:08:51.919 --> 00:08:56.159
So WebAssembly, or sometimes called WASM,

00:08:56.159 --> 00:09:00.479
is a low-level, high-performance binary instruction

00:09:01.479 --> 00:09:05.840
and it allows compiled languages like C or C++

00:09:05.840 --> 00:09:10.039
to run in web browsers at near native speeds.

00:09:10.039 --> 00:09:15.039
So C and C++ code is compiled by something called Emscripten.

00:09:15.880 --> 00:09:20.640
Emscripten takes the C or C++ code as input.

00:09:20.640 --> 00:09:23.119
It produces WASM as a result.

00:09:23.119 --> 00:09:25.000
And once it's in WASM,

00:09:25.000 --> 00:09:29.359
you can run it in any browser that supports WASM,

00:09:29.559 --> 00:09:32.400
which in modern browsers is actually most of them.

00:09:34.960 --> 00:09:37.359
Python has had a browser solution

00:09:37.359 --> 00:09:39.640
for a while called Pyodide.

00:09:39.640 --> 00:09:41.960
So what Pyodide does is compiles

00:09:41.960 --> 00:09:45.960
the Python interpreter CPython to WebAssembly

00:09:45.960 --> 00:09:48.640
using Emscripten, and then it makes it possible

00:09:48.640 --> 00:09:51.119
to run Python in the browser.

00:09:52.479 --> 00:09:54.400
And relatively more recently,

00:09:54.400 --> 00:09:58.320
now R has a similar solution with WebR.

00:09:58.320 --> 00:10:01.320
So WebR is the WebAssembly version of R

00:10:01.320 --> 00:10:04.280
that has been compiled to run in the browser.

00:10:04.280 --> 00:10:07.760
It's an open-source project primarily driven by Posit,

00:10:07.760 --> 00:10:10.359
and thanks to the amazing work of many folks,

00:10:10.359 --> 00:10:13.280
but especially George Stagg and Lionel Henry,

00:10:13.280 --> 00:10:17.320
it's now possible to run R code directly in a web browser

00:10:17.320 --> 00:10:21.280
without the need of traditional servers to execute the code.

00:10:21.280 --> 00:10:23.039
So essentially what that means

00:10:23.039 --> 00:10:27.919
is a user can visit a website and run R code directly,

00:10:27.919 --> 00:10:31.200
so without needing R installed on their device.

00:10:31.200 --> 00:10:34.400
All that is required is a web host server

00:10:34.400 --> 00:10:38.119
like Netlify or GitHub Pages.

00:10:40.039 --> 00:10:41.960
So let's see what this actually looks like.

00:10:41.960 --> 00:10:46.039
This is a web-based interactive R console

00:10:46.039 --> 00:10:49.000
that's included in the WebR source repo

00:10:49.000 --> 00:10:52.039
as a demonstration of integrating WebR

00:10:52.039 --> 00:10:54.239
in a wider web application.

00:10:54.239 --> 00:10:57.760
So it provides a simple R environment in your web browser

00:10:57.760 --> 00:10:59.679
and includes things like code input,

00:10:59.679 --> 00:11:04.039
output, code editing, file management, and graphics.

00:11:04.039 --> 00:11:08.159
So if I click this, this is the URL,

00:11:08.159 --> 00:11:10.039
and I can share this with others.

00:11:10.039 --> 00:11:11.679
I could share this with you,

00:11:11.679 --> 00:11:14.880
and you may notice it kind of looks like RStudio.

00:11:14.880 --> 00:11:17.159
They did a really nice job designing it

00:11:17.159 --> 00:11:21.880
so that if you are an RStudio user, it looks very familiar.

00:11:21.880 --> 00:11:25.799
You have your console down here and your plots here,

00:11:25.799 --> 00:11:28.599
and even though it looks like RStudio, though,

00:11:28.599 --> 00:11:32.799
remember, this is completely being run in the browser.

00:11:32.799 --> 00:11:35.599
There was nothing installed from our end.

00:11:35.599 --> 00:11:37.880
There was nothing that we had to set up,

00:11:37.880 --> 00:11:42.880
and I can do something like install packages ggplot2.

00:11:50.559 --> 00:11:51.799
Dangerous of live coding.

00:11:51.799 --> 00:11:52.640
There we go.

00:11:52.640 --> 00:11:54.119
So it says installing packages,

00:11:54.159 --> 00:11:57.000
and you'll notice it says downloading WebR package.

00:11:57.000 --> 00:11:59.479
We'll talk a little bit more about that,

00:11:59.479 --> 00:12:01.239
but even though it looks familiar,

00:12:01.239 --> 00:12:04.159
again, everything is being done in the browser.

00:12:04.159 --> 00:12:09.159
I can go up here into my R script and do library ggplot2,

00:12:10.599 --> 00:12:15.599
run that, and then I do ggplot ntcars as x equals mpg,

00:12:15.599 --> 00:12:20.599
ntcars as x equals mpg, y equals hp, plus geom point,

00:12:28.479 --> 00:12:31.280
and then it produces the plot.

00:12:31.280 --> 00:12:33.239
So it's pretty amazing.

00:12:33.239 --> 00:12:34.520
So say you have somebody,

00:12:34.520 --> 00:12:38.479
for whatever reason they can't install RStudio,

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:40.080
but they really want to learn R,

00:12:40.080 --> 00:12:41.880
you can send them this URL,

00:12:41.880 --> 00:12:44.000
and they can try things out on their own.

00:12:45.599 --> 00:12:50.599
So I mentioned a bit about packages.

00:12:55.359 --> 00:12:57.760
So in terms of PyDyed,

00:12:57.760 --> 00:12:59.599
it includes a package manager

00:12:59.599 --> 00:13:02.000
that allows the use of Python packages.

00:13:02.000 --> 00:13:04.039
You can also install Python wheels

00:13:04.039 --> 00:13:07.559
or load custom Python packages with PyDyed.

00:13:07.559 --> 00:13:09.159
And then on the R side,

00:13:09.159 --> 00:13:13.719
there's over 14,000 R packages available for WebR.

00:13:13.719 --> 00:13:14.799
A bit of a caveat.

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:16.159
So the way that this works

00:13:16.159 --> 00:13:19.599
is that R packages have to be compiled for Wasm.

00:13:19.599 --> 00:13:21.440
That's why the installed package

00:13:21.440 --> 00:13:23.760
looked a little bit different.

00:13:23.760 --> 00:13:28.760
And so the 14,000 number comes from 14,000 R packages

00:13:29.000 --> 00:13:31.440
that were compiled to Wasm without error,

00:13:31.440 --> 00:13:33.960
but they haven't all necessarily been tested.

00:13:33.960 --> 00:13:37.679
So again, just a bit of a caveat there,

00:13:37.679 --> 00:13:41.280
but still a lot of packages are available,

00:13:41.280 --> 00:13:44.119
especially the ones that are very popular and well-known

00:13:44.159 --> 00:13:47.960
like tidy models and tidyverse and things like that.

00:13:47.960 --> 00:13:50.359
So when you are installing packages,

00:13:50.359 --> 00:13:53.599
by default, the WebR install function

00:13:53.599 --> 00:13:55.719
will use the public repository

00:13:55.719 --> 00:13:59.599
hosted at repos.rwasm.org.

00:13:59.599 --> 00:14:04.599
And then say like you also want to

00:14:04.599 --> 00:14:09.080
use your own personal package for use in WebR.

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:11.880
So there is a project called R Universe.

00:14:11.880 --> 00:14:14.000
It's a project by R OpenSci

00:14:14.880 --> 00:14:17.520
that experiments with ideas for improving the publication

00:14:17.520 --> 00:14:20.840
and discovery of research software in R.

00:14:20.840 --> 00:14:24.359
And R Universe builds Wasm binaries for R packages

00:14:24.359 --> 00:14:26.799
for use in WebR applications.

00:14:26.799 --> 00:14:28.799
So if you have a custom package,

00:14:28.799 --> 00:14:31.039
the easiest way to get up and running

00:14:31.039 --> 00:14:34.880
is to create an R Universe repo for your packages.

00:14:34.880 --> 00:14:38.479
And then the system will automatically build R binaries

00:14:38.479 --> 00:14:41.080
for different things, including WebAssembly.

00:14:41.080 --> 00:14:43.960
And then you can use that in WebR.

00:14:43.960 --> 00:14:45.840
And so there are other options.

00:14:45.840 --> 00:14:48.880
There's an rwasm package and things like that,

00:14:48.880 --> 00:14:52.359
but just wanted to highlight that is the recommended

00:14:52.359 --> 00:14:54.880
easiest or quickest way to get started.

00:14:57.640 --> 00:14:59.479
In terms of how to use WebR,

00:14:59.479 --> 00:15:02.320
if you go to the WebR documentation linked here,

00:15:03.440 --> 00:15:06.559
it's very robust and very detailed.

00:15:06.559 --> 00:15:09.280
But if you're like me, you look at the front page

00:15:09.320 --> 00:15:14.039
and it says, install the package, npm i WebR.

00:15:14.919 --> 00:15:16.280
And you're like, okay.

00:15:16.280 --> 00:15:18.239
And then import the WebR class.

00:15:18.239 --> 00:15:19.799
And it has this.

00:15:19.799 --> 00:15:22.880
And then you realize like, oh, this is JavaScript.

00:15:22.880 --> 00:15:26.559
So what if you don't know JavaScript like me?

00:15:26.559 --> 00:15:27.400
It's the edge.

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:30.640
So WebR, it doesn't seem to be as quick and easy

00:15:30.640 --> 00:15:32.559
to use for those who do.

00:15:32.559 --> 00:15:36.119
But if you don't, what options do you have?

00:15:36.119 --> 00:15:38.760
And that is where Cordo comes in.

00:15:40.280 --> 00:15:45.200
Cordo is a next generation open source publishing system.

00:15:45.200 --> 00:15:48.200
So it is often called the next evolution

00:15:48.200 --> 00:15:51.080
or the next generation of our markdown.

00:15:51.080 --> 00:15:53.719
So it's expanded upon our markdown.

00:15:53.719 --> 00:15:56.559
What we have done at Posit is taken everything

00:15:56.559 --> 00:15:59.119
that we learned over the past 10 years

00:15:59.119 --> 00:16:02.679
to develop a system like Cordo.

00:16:02.679 --> 00:16:06.640
One of the things about Cordo, it's inherently multilingual.

00:16:06.679 --> 00:16:11.280
So right now it supports R, Python, Julia and Observable,

00:16:11.280 --> 00:16:14.760
but it's been designed so that we can add new languages

00:16:14.760 --> 00:16:16.039
in the future.

00:16:17.080 --> 00:16:19.799
Another thing that we've learned is R markdown

00:16:19.799 --> 00:16:23.119
has a lot of packages that does a lot of things.

00:16:23.119 --> 00:16:24.840
If you are an R markdown user,

00:16:24.840 --> 00:16:27.919
you might know like use shringen if you wanna do slides

00:16:27.919 --> 00:16:30.640
and bookdown if you wanna do books.

00:16:30.640 --> 00:16:32.520
But Cordo has a shared expression

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:34.359
for all these core features.

00:16:34.359 --> 00:16:38.520
So what that means is if you do a tab set in a Cordo book,

00:16:38.520 --> 00:16:42.840
it looks the same as a tab set in a Cordo presentation.

00:16:42.840 --> 00:16:46.919
And the idea behind Cordo is to create dynamic content

00:16:46.919 --> 00:16:50.880
with Python and R and Julia and Observable.

00:16:50.880 --> 00:16:53.599
And then another thing is it enables

00:16:53.599 --> 00:16:55.039
single source publishing.

00:16:55.039 --> 00:16:58.119
So the idea of creating notebooks or dashboards

00:16:58.119 --> 00:17:01.239
or books, et cetera, from one source.

00:17:01.239 --> 00:17:05.560
And I will say there are many great resources about Cordo.

00:17:05.560 --> 00:17:08.599
We're not gonna talk about everything about Cordo.

00:17:08.599 --> 00:17:11.680
At this time, I'm happy to share the resources.

00:17:11.680 --> 00:17:14.880
I would say that the Cordo documentation site

00:17:14.880 --> 00:17:16.640
is absolutely incredible.

00:17:16.640 --> 00:17:19.640
It is very detailed and how to get started,

00:17:19.640 --> 00:17:21.319
how to use Cordo.

00:17:21.319 --> 00:17:24.640
I gave a talk a couple of years ago at R Ladies St. Louis

00:17:24.640 --> 00:17:27.199
that I'm happy to share that went more into detail

00:17:27.199 --> 00:17:30.359
in terms of like, you know, getting set up in R studio

00:17:30.400 --> 00:17:32.839
and rendering documents and things like that.

00:17:32.839 --> 00:17:35.079
But for today, I'm just going to be talking

00:17:35.079 --> 00:17:37.800
about the most critical parts of Cordo

00:17:37.800 --> 00:17:41.880
that you need to know in order to use WebR

00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:44.680
and PyEdite in Cordo documents.

00:17:46.719 --> 00:17:49.400
So first, the anatomy of a Cordo document.

00:17:49.400 --> 00:17:53.239
So a Cordo document has an extension QMD.

00:17:53.239 --> 00:17:55.280
The first part that we're going to talk about

00:17:55.280 --> 00:17:58.119
is what is called the YAML heading.

00:17:58.119 --> 00:18:01.040
So it is denoted by these three dashes

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:04.680
and then a key value pairs within these dashes.

00:18:04.680 --> 00:18:07.280
So the key, for example, can be title

00:18:07.280 --> 00:18:10.880
and the value is ggplot2-demo.

00:18:10.880 --> 00:18:14.040
And the YAML heading contains the metadata

00:18:14.040 --> 00:18:15.359
for your document.

00:18:15.359 --> 00:18:17.119
So in this case, it's saying,

00:18:17.119 --> 00:18:20.439
I want to produce an HTML format.

00:18:20.439 --> 00:18:24.520
I can provide additional options like code full true

00:18:24.520 --> 00:18:27.199
means like the code within the document

00:18:27.199 --> 00:18:30.760
should collapse so that it's not immediately visible

00:18:30.760 --> 00:18:34.280
unless somebody clicks it to open it up.

00:18:34.280 --> 00:18:37.560
And so the YAML heading, just to reiterate,

00:18:37.560 --> 00:18:40.719
is the kind of metadata of your document.

00:18:42.359 --> 00:18:45.479
The next part to talk about is the markdown text.

00:18:45.479 --> 00:18:50.479
So markdown is a lightweight way of writing formatted text

00:18:50.880 --> 00:18:54.880
and in a way that it looks very readable.

00:18:54.880 --> 00:18:58.920
You can do things like, for example, here in line eight,

00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:01.400
the two pound signs mean this is a heading.

00:19:01.400 --> 00:19:03.640
So this will be rendered as a heading.

00:19:03.640 --> 00:19:08.640
You can do things like embed images, links, tables,

00:19:08.760 --> 00:19:11.239
format your text, all sorts of things.

00:19:11.239 --> 00:19:13.239
But the really nice thing about markdown

00:19:13.239 --> 00:19:18.239
is that once you learn it, it's easily readable

00:19:18.760 --> 00:19:22.239
when you say, put it up on GitHub.

00:19:22.319 --> 00:19:25.520
It doesn't come out in a very nested,

00:19:25.520 --> 00:19:26.839
difficult to read format.

00:19:26.839 --> 00:19:28.520
It looks like text.

00:19:30.800 --> 00:19:34.439
The next part of the next anatomy of the Cordo document

00:19:34.439 --> 00:19:36.520
is what are called code chunks.

00:19:36.520 --> 00:19:38.800
So those are denoted by three back ticks

00:19:38.800 --> 00:19:40.959
and then in curly braces,

00:19:40.959 --> 00:19:43.319
the programming language that you want.

00:19:43.319 --> 00:19:44.719
And within this code chunk

00:19:44.719 --> 00:19:46.880
is going to be your executable code.

00:19:46.880 --> 00:19:50.839
So this is code that is actually going to run.

00:19:50.839 --> 00:19:54.880
And so there are these things called code chunk options.

00:19:54.880 --> 00:19:56.839
They're denoted by the pound sign

00:19:56.839 --> 00:20:00.079
and then the long vertical line.

00:20:00.079 --> 00:20:02.640
I think that is called a hash pipe.

00:20:02.640 --> 00:20:06.680
And this provides metadata for your code chunks.

00:20:06.680 --> 00:20:09.920
So in this case, it's saying label,

00:20:09.920 --> 00:20:12.400
label this plot, plot penguins.

00:20:12.400 --> 00:20:16.199
Echo is false means that you do not want to see

00:20:16.199 --> 00:20:17.479
the actual code chunk.

00:20:17.479 --> 00:20:20.520
All you want to do is see the output message

00:20:21.199 --> 00:20:23.280
and warning is if this code produces a message

00:20:23.280 --> 00:20:25.520
and warning, do not show it.

00:20:25.520 --> 00:20:27.760
And there are other kinds of things

00:20:27.760 --> 00:20:32.359
in terms of like handling how things are actually rendered

00:20:32.359 --> 00:20:35.000
when you render your document from a QMD file

00:20:35.000 --> 00:20:37.280
to say an HTML document.

00:20:39.119 --> 00:20:42.839
And then within the code chunk is your actual code.

00:20:42.839 --> 00:20:47.479
So in this case, you know, the library,

00:20:47.479 --> 00:20:51.199
sorry, the packages tidyverse and palmer penguins will run.

00:20:51.199 --> 00:20:53.680
It will create this ggplot code.

00:20:53.680 --> 00:20:55.479
And when you click render on this document,

00:20:55.479 --> 00:20:57.359
that code is actually going to run.

00:20:58.880 --> 00:21:01.119
And so this is a quick look of what it looks like

00:21:01.119 --> 00:21:03.800
when you actually hit render.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:06.680
So all of that, you know, text and code

00:21:06.680 --> 00:21:10.280
and labels that you wrote is going to output

00:21:10.280 --> 00:21:13.000
this HTML document that looks like this.

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:14.560
If you notice, you can't see the code

00:21:14.560 --> 00:21:17.160
because you said, please do not show me the code.

00:21:17.839 --> 00:21:19.239
There's a link and everything like that

00:21:19.239 --> 00:21:21.119
that came from the markdown text.

00:21:22.959 --> 00:21:27.319
Another critical part for today are Cordo extensions.

00:21:27.319 --> 00:21:29.560
So Cordo extensions let you customize

00:21:29.560 --> 00:21:31.680
and extend Cordo's functionality

00:21:31.680 --> 00:21:34.160
beyond its built-in features.

00:21:34.160 --> 00:21:36.680
So things like new output formats,

00:21:36.680 --> 00:21:39.920
so custom templates for the documents

00:21:39.920 --> 00:21:41.280
that you want to create.

00:21:41.280 --> 00:21:44.839
A relatively recent one is the scrolly telling extension.

00:21:44.839 --> 00:21:47.719
So if you've ever seen those kinds of journalism articles

00:21:47.719 --> 00:21:50.839
that as you scroll through, they highlight different plots

00:21:50.839 --> 00:21:53.920
or different parts of a plot or things like that,

00:21:53.920 --> 00:21:56.280
that is now possible with Cordo

00:21:56.280 --> 00:21:58.719
thanks to the scrolly telling extension.

00:21:59.520 --> 00:22:02.800
Another example is journal articles.

00:22:02.800 --> 00:22:06.040
So you can install extensions.

00:22:06.040 --> 00:22:08.880
So if you are trying to say,

00:22:08.880 --> 00:22:12.560
like submit to the journal statistical software

00:22:12.560 --> 00:22:14.520
so that your Cordo document renders

00:22:15.119 --> 00:22:16.959
in the format that they require.

00:22:16.959 --> 00:22:19.560
Things like reveal.js themes.

00:22:19.560 --> 00:22:22.359
So presentations in Cordo are done

00:22:22.359 --> 00:22:25.040
in a format called reveal.js.

00:22:25.040 --> 00:22:29.560
And there are extensions out there so that you can see,

00:22:29.560 --> 00:22:32.359
so you can customize what your reveal.js extension

00:22:32.359 --> 00:22:33.599
will look like.

00:22:33.599 --> 00:22:35.880
So unique styling and layouts

00:22:35.880 --> 00:22:40.079
and all sorts of other ways of modifying

00:22:40.079 --> 00:22:42.640
how Cordo processes content.

00:22:42.640 --> 00:22:44.920
So one example that I have

00:22:47.479 --> 00:22:50.239
is one that I use for the presentation today.

00:22:50.239 --> 00:22:52.839
So there is a font awesome extension.

00:22:53.760 --> 00:22:57.079
And how to use extensions is first you install the extension

00:22:57.079 --> 00:22:59.280
and then a quick note,

00:22:59.280 --> 00:23:02.359
Cordo extensions, if you go to their GitHub repo

00:23:02.359 --> 00:23:03.839
or their documentation page,

00:23:03.839 --> 00:23:07.359
generally have instructions as to how to install it

00:23:07.359 --> 00:23:09.239
and how to actually use it.

00:23:09.239 --> 00:23:12.239
So each one might be slightly different,

00:23:12.239 --> 00:23:13.760
and so you definitely want to go

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:15.599
and check their documentation

00:23:15.599 --> 00:23:18.359
if there is an extension that you want to use.

00:23:18.359 --> 00:23:20.079
But for the font awesome extension,

00:23:20.079 --> 00:23:22.560
you install it, you say Cordo add,

00:23:22.560 --> 00:23:26.599
Cordo ext font awesome in the terminal.

00:23:26.599 --> 00:23:28.599
And then in your Cordo document,

00:23:28.599 --> 00:23:32.599
the YAML heading under, you add a filters option

00:23:32.599 --> 00:23:35.199
and then list out the different extensions

00:23:35.199 --> 00:23:36.119
that you want to include.

00:23:36.119 --> 00:23:38.920
So in this case, filters font awesome.

00:23:39.920 --> 00:23:43.319
And then to use the extension of the doc,

00:23:43.319 --> 00:23:46.800
anywhere that I want to put, say, a GitHub icon,

00:23:46.800 --> 00:23:50.119
I put this short code with the curly braces.

00:23:50.119 --> 00:23:52.520
And then when I actually rendered the document,

00:23:52.520 --> 00:23:55.520
it results in the GitHub icon.

00:23:55.520 --> 00:23:58.400
So that's an example of a Cordo extension.

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:01.479
That being said, there are so many available

00:24:01.479 --> 00:24:05.839
and here is a link to the Cordo extension gallery

00:24:05.839 --> 00:24:07.920
by Mikhail Makhnoly.

00:24:07.920 --> 00:24:12.520
And so if you want to search for different extensions

00:24:12.520 --> 00:24:17.000
and see what's out there, this is a great place to start.

00:24:17.000 --> 00:24:22.000
Another note is that Cordo extensions are Lua-based

00:24:22.359 --> 00:24:25.280
and if you feel comfortable writing in that,

00:24:25.280 --> 00:24:27.560
you can also make your own extensions

00:24:27.560 --> 00:24:30.000
if there is something that you require

00:24:30.000 --> 00:24:32.959
and you don't see out there in the wild.

00:24:34.760 --> 00:24:36.119
So wrapping everything up,

00:24:36.119 --> 00:24:38.800
we started off talking about WebAssembly

00:24:38.800 --> 00:24:41.719
and how the technologies behind WebAssembly

00:24:41.719 --> 00:24:44.319
enable Pyodai and WebR,

00:24:44.319 --> 00:24:48.760
which allow you to run R and Python in the browser

00:24:48.760 --> 00:24:53.479
like we saw with the web-based R console.

00:24:53.479 --> 00:24:57.359
But to use those, you need to know JavaScript.

00:24:57.359 --> 00:25:01.280
And so we went into a brief introduction of Cordo

00:25:01.280 --> 00:25:06.000
because with Cordo, there is an extension called Cordo Live.

00:25:06.880 --> 00:25:09.079
And Cordo Live allows you to embed

00:25:09.079 --> 00:25:11.199
WebAssembly-powered code blocks

00:25:11.199 --> 00:25:13.959
and exercises in Cordo documents

00:25:13.959 --> 00:25:16.239
through the Cordo Live extension.

00:25:16.239 --> 00:25:19.400
And there's support for both R via WebR

00:25:19.400 --> 00:25:22.479
and Python via Pyodai.

00:25:22.479 --> 00:25:26.199
And features include interactive code blocks,

00:25:26.199 --> 00:25:28.880
exercises with hints and solutions,

00:25:28.880 --> 00:25:30.800
and rich output like plots.

00:25:30.800 --> 00:25:32.479
And the most important thing,

00:25:32.520 --> 00:25:34.319
WebAssembly and Python skills are not needed

00:25:34.319 --> 00:25:37.280
to use WebR in your content.

00:25:37.280 --> 00:25:39.520
And I did also want to briefly mention

00:25:39.520 --> 00:25:42.359
that originally there was an extension

00:25:42.359 --> 00:25:45.880
by James Balamuta called Cordo WebR,

00:25:45.880 --> 00:25:49.560
but Cordo Live is the extension

00:25:49.560 --> 00:25:51.199
that is supported by Posit.

00:25:52.319 --> 00:25:54.520
So let's see what this actually looks like.

00:25:55.479 --> 00:25:58.479
So Cordo Live, again,

00:25:58.479 --> 00:26:01.520
embeds these WebAssembly-powered blocks

00:26:01.520 --> 00:26:04.160
for R or Python into Cordo documents.

00:26:04.160 --> 00:26:05.280
So after a little bit,

00:26:05.280 --> 00:26:07.400
you're going to see this editor

00:26:07.400 --> 00:26:10.319
with a button that says run code.

00:26:11.359 --> 00:26:12.719
And if I click this,

00:26:14.359 --> 00:26:17.920
I have run R code in my browser

00:26:17.920 --> 00:26:21.280
from a presentation that I created in Cordo.

00:26:21.280 --> 00:26:22.719
It is pretty amazing.

00:26:24.239 --> 00:26:25.880
I think it's very cool.

00:26:26.719 --> 00:26:29.160
So another thing to note, this is an editor,

00:26:29.160 --> 00:26:31.079
so I can change whatever I'd like.

00:26:31.640 --> 00:26:33.479
So say I want to do one through six.

00:26:33.479 --> 00:26:36.560
Oh, oh, sorry.

00:26:36.560 --> 00:26:37.920
I don't know what happened.

00:26:43.199 --> 00:26:45.599
The presentation got, I'm sorry, one second.

00:26:51.920 --> 00:26:52.760
Here.

00:26:58.160 --> 00:26:59.000
I am back.

00:27:01.079 --> 00:27:01.920
Okay.

00:27:07.439 --> 00:27:08.280
Okay.

00:27:08.280 --> 00:27:11.040
Hopefully, if you cannot see it, just let me know.

00:27:11.040 --> 00:27:14.439
But okay, so I've changed this from one to five

00:27:14.439 --> 00:27:16.479
to one to six.

00:27:16.479 --> 00:27:21.400
Let's say print instead of X to the power of two,

00:27:21.400 --> 00:27:23.479
X to the power of three.

00:27:23.479 --> 00:27:24.880
We can run code.

00:27:24.880 --> 00:27:28.280
And then again, it just executes that code

00:27:28.280 --> 00:27:31.280
in the browser from my presentation.

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:39.319
So in terms of how to actually use this,

00:27:39.319 --> 00:27:40.680
it's going to look very similar

00:27:40.680 --> 00:27:42.199
to what we talked about before.

00:27:42.199 --> 00:27:46.079
First, you install the extension in the terminal,

00:27:46.079 --> 00:27:49.599
and then you add to your Cordo document YAML header.

00:27:49.599 --> 00:27:51.359
If you notice, it looks slightly different.

00:27:51.359 --> 00:27:53.400
So instead of putting it under filters,

00:27:53.400 --> 00:27:55.280
we put it under format,

00:27:55.280 --> 00:27:59.439
and we change it from, say, HTML to live HTML.

00:28:01.920 --> 00:28:04.520
A quick note is by default,

00:28:04.520 --> 00:28:08.959
the Cordo live extension uses Pyodied for Python.

00:28:08.959 --> 00:28:12.760
So if you want to use the Cordo live extension

00:28:12.760 --> 00:28:14.839
for NIDAR and R,

00:28:14.839 --> 00:28:17.920
then you have to include the engine,

00:28:17.920 --> 00:28:20.359
engine NIDAR in your YAML heading.

00:28:20.359 --> 00:28:22.760
And then you also have to include the shortcode

00:28:22.760 --> 00:28:24.680
that you see on line six as well.

00:28:26.280 --> 00:28:29.560
Then to use Cordo live in a Cordo document,

00:28:29.560 --> 00:28:33.119
you place your code in either a WebR code chunk for R

00:28:33.119 --> 00:28:35.560
or a Pyodied code chunk for Python.

00:28:35.560 --> 00:28:39.959
And so the chunk that you saw a little bit earlier,

00:28:39.959 --> 00:28:42.199
this is what I have in my document

00:28:42.199 --> 00:28:46.640
in order to create that live editor that executes code.

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:52.119
A note is you can use Cordo live in your presentations too.

00:28:52.160 --> 00:28:55.359
So when you're creating a Cordo presentation,

00:28:55.359 --> 00:28:57.640
you have format reveal JS,

00:28:57.640 --> 00:29:02.640
and then you edit your YAML header to live reveal JS.

00:29:03.719 --> 00:29:05.640
Another cool thing that you can do,

00:29:05.640 --> 00:29:10.239
say, if you want to use Cordo, sorry,

00:29:10.239 --> 00:29:12.280
Cordo live in your presentations

00:29:12.280 --> 00:29:15.359
is you can install the Cordo drop extension.

00:29:15.359 --> 00:29:16.640
You press the back tick,

00:29:16.640 --> 00:29:20.760
and then this console for R or Python can drop down.

00:29:20.760 --> 00:29:25.760
And then again, you can just start typing R code

00:29:26.079 --> 00:29:29.520
and then execute it in real time.

00:29:29.520 --> 00:29:32.239
And so you can imagine, say you're giving a lecture,

00:29:32.239 --> 00:29:34.760
somebody asks like, how would you do this in R?

00:29:34.760 --> 00:29:37.239
You can just go ahead, drop in R console,

00:29:37.239 --> 00:29:38.920
try it out, and then lift it up

00:29:38.920 --> 00:29:42.560
and continue on with your presentation.

00:29:46.000 --> 00:29:48.079
In terms of other kinds of options

00:29:48.079 --> 00:29:50.680
that are included in Cordo live,

00:29:51.439 --> 00:29:53.239
there are things like you can create breed only cells.

00:29:53.239 --> 00:29:55.640
So once that you can actually be edited,

00:29:55.640 --> 00:29:57.839
nope, I didn't realize it's not full screen.

00:30:00.079 --> 00:30:01.479
You can auto run.

00:30:01.479 --> 00:30:05.280
So instead of needing somebody to click run code

00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:08.959
in order to see the output, you can have it auto run.

00:30:08.959 --> 00:30:12.160
You can have auto complete within the editor if you want,

00:30:12.160 --> 00:30:13.000
and much more.

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:15.959
So recommend looking at the documentation

00:30:15.959 --> 00:30:19.119
if you want to see all the things that are possible.

00:30:20.119 --> 00:30:23.079
And back to the idea of installing packages,

00:30:23.079 --> 00:30:25.439
you have a couple options here too.

00:30:25.439 --> 00:30:28.359
You can install packages as the document loads.

00:30:28.359 --> 00:30:31.160
So in this case, whenever somebody opens

00:30:31.160 --> 00:30:32.599
the rendered document,

00:30:32.599 --> 00:30:35.560
WebR is going to load dplyr,

00:30:35.560 --> 00:30:38.439
Palmer penguins and ggplot2.

00:30:38.439 --> 00:30:42.719
And so of course, depending on the size of your packages,

00:30:42.719 --> 00:30:44.719
it might take a little while.

00:30:44.719 --> 00:30:48.359
Since I had this presentation already open when we started,

00:30:48.359 --> 00:30:49.880
there's like a little loading message

00:30:49.880 --> 00:30:52.599
that lets me know like these packages are being loaded.

00:30:52.599 --> 00:30:56.800
And so the run code will show up once it's ready to go.

00:30:58.160 --> 00:31:00.239
And then another option is interactively.

00:31:00.239 --> 00:31:02.920
So if you would rather install the packages

00:31:02.920 --> 00:31:05.640
as and load them as you,

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:08.439
as your user actually goes through the document,

00:31:08.439 --> 00:31:12.040
you can include this in your WebR or pylide chunk.

00:31:12.040 --> 00:31:13.880
And so whenever they click run code,

00:31:13.880 --> 00:31:16.000
that's when the package will be installed.

00:31:18.719 --> 00:31:20.000
Well, a few more examples.

00:31:20.000 --> 00:31:23.760
We mentioned like WebR and portal live

00:31:23.760 --> 00:31:26.119
allows you to display plots.

00:31:26.119 --> 00:31:29.239
So here we have this base R plot.

00:31:30.520 --> 00:31:34.959
I can click that and then see an example plot.

00:31:34.959 --> 00:31:36.599
And just a thing to note too,

00:31:36.599 --> 00:31:39.640
that graphics work a bit different than normal

00:31:39.640 --> 00:31:42.000
than they do like in regular R.

00:31:42.000 --> 00:31:44.280
And this is because there's something called

00:31:44.280 --> 00:31:47.359
a graphics device that implements the drawing commands

00:31:47.359 --> 00:31:49.199
from R in the browser.

00:31:49.199 --> 00:31:52.839
But one benefit of this is that it takes advantage

00:31:52.839 --> 00:31:56.520
of features that exist in browsers already.

00:31:56.520 --> 00:32:00.800
So things like fonts from other languages or emojis,

00:32:00.800 --> 00:32:03.479
that's already built in, which is pretty cool.

00:32:03.479 --> 00:32:05.119
Let's say I'm seeing this and I'm like,

00:32:05.119 --> 00:32:06.079
oh, I like this plot.

00:32:06.079 --> 00:32:08.239
Oh no, I have a typo.

00:32:08.239 --> 00:32:11.319
I can go ahead, pick that typo,

00:32:11.319 --> 00:32:13.160
rerun code and get a plot

00:32:13.160 --> 00:32:15.160
that actually looks the way that I want.

00:32:18.359 --> 00:32:23.280
Another example is creating exercises with portal live.

00:32:23.280 --> 00:32:26.959
So you can designate a chunk as an exercise.

00:32:26.959 --> 00:32:29.599
So this chunk says fill in the blanks

00:32:29.599 --> 00:32:32.199
so that the result of the sum is 10.

00:32:32.199 --> 00:32:35.319
I'm like, oh boy, I don't know what to do.

00:32:35.319 --> 00:32:38.680
I can show a hint and then it tells me

00:32:38.680 --> 00:32:42.160
consider subtracting one, two, three from 10.

00:32:42.160 --> 00:32:44.199
I'm like, oh no, I still don't know.

00:32:44.239 --> 00:32:47.920
Let's say I put five and I click run code.

00:32:47.920 --> 00:32:50.079
It's going to tell me the output

00:32:50.079 --> 00:32:52.359
and then let me know that's incorrect.

00:32:52.359 --> 00:32:55.599
And say I give up, I can say show solution

00:32:55.599 --> 00:32:58.199
and then it lets me know what the solution is.

00:33:01.160 --> 00:33:03.599
So you can imagine for teaching,

00:33:03.599 --> 00:33:06.439
there's a lot of different kinds of applications.

00:33:06.439 --> 00:33:10.280
And so here is one from Klaus Wilke

00:33:10.280 --> 00:33:12.760
on the introduction to R.

00:33:12.800 --> 00:33:14.680
I open this up.

00:33:14.680 --> 00:33:17.680
You'll see that Buzzer has created

00:33:17.680 --> 00:33:19.520
this interactive document.

00:33:19.520 --> 00:33:22.439
Here is the loading icon.

00:33:22.439 --> 00:33:25.199
So we know like the packages are not quite ready yet,

00:33:25.199 --> 00:33:28.560
but it seems like they are being installed

00:33:28.560 --> 00:33:30.520
as soon as you load the document.

00:33:30.520 --> 00:33:33.520
And then, okay, it looks like it's ready to go.

00:33:33.520 --> 00:33:36.760
And then there's all these different exercises

00:33:36.760 --> 00:33:38.439
that you can go through.

00:33:38.439 --> 00:33:40.640
And if you imagine there's somebody

00:33:40.640 --> 00:33:43.199
you're trying to teach introduction to R,

00:33:43.199 --> 00:33:46.719
here's a great way of making things like really interactive

00:33:47.599 --> 00:33:51.760
and without like needing that much more to set up

00:33:51.760 --> 00:33:53.400
beyond the quarter document

00:33:53.400 --> 00:33:56.239
that you've created for your lecture.

00:34:02.000 --> 00:34:04.920
Another self-promotion that I wanted to give

00:34:04.920 --> 00:34:07.280
is that I wrote this blog post

00:34:07.280 --> 00:34:10.679
called Six Not-So-Basic Base R Functions a while back.

00:34:10.679 --> 00:34:14.120
And a quick note that this used the Cordo WebR extension,

00:34:14.959 --> 00:34:18.040
not Cordo Live because Cordo Live wasn't quite out yet,

00:34:18.040 --> 00:34:20.840
but just wanted to show like essentially

00:34:20.840 --> 00:34:22.080
the same kind of ideas.

00:34:22.080 --> 00:34:24.879
I wanted to highlight these base R functions

00:34:24.879 --> 00:34:27.080
and somebody could go in here and run

00:34:27.080 --> 00:34:31.199
and see like what changes and try things out.

00:34:32.199 --> 00:34:33.879
And then also there's an example

00:34:33.879 --> 00:34:36.479
of what installing packages could look like.

00:34:36.479 --> 00:34:40.239
So this, for example, is a package that's not on CRAN.

00:34:40.239 --> 00:34:43.560
It is my older brother's package.

00:34:43.560 --> 00:34:48.560
And so then I can designate his R universe repository

00:34:48.919 --> 00:34:52.040
in order to install it and use it in the examples.

00:34:57.560 --> 00:34:58.760
I know that that's a lot,

00:34:58.760 --> 00:35:02.959
but I really hope like this conveys like the excitement

00:35:02.959 --> 00:35:06.199
and the amazingness that I think this technology brings.

00:35:06.919 --> 00:35:09.320
And so thanks, Adam, for this note.

00:35:10.439 --> 00:35:13.280
I hope he's not actually weeping real tears,

00:35:13.280 --> 00:35:15.399
but it truly is so amazing

00:35:15.399 --> 00:35:17.199
that sometimes it feels like magic.

00:35:19.399 --> 00:35:21.560
So we've talked about Cordo documents

00:35:21.560 --> 00:35:24.360
and executable R chunks and things like that,

00:35:24.360 --> 00:35:28.320
but you might be wondering, well, what about Shiny?

00:35:28.320 --> 00:35:30.199
And if you are new to Shiny,

00:35:30.199 --> 00:35:33.479
Shiny allows you to create web applications

00:35:33.520 --> 00:35:36.439
without needing to know JavaScript, HTML,

00:35:36.439 --> 00:35:38.280
or anything like that.

00:35:38.280 --> 00:35:40.959
You can just do it in pure R or pure Python,

00:35:40.959 --> 00:35:43.040
which is pretty amazing

00:35:43.040 --> 00:35:45.159
if you don't know JavaScript like me.

00:35:46.320 --> 00:35:49.919
But say you've created your Shiny dashboard,

00:35:49.919 --> 00:35:52.520
very beautiful, ready to go.

00:35:52.520 --> 00:35:55.959
And then you need to share it with somebody.

00:35:55.959 --> 00:35:58.600
So the traditional Shiny architecture

00:35:59.439 --> 00:36:01.879
for deploying a Shiny app

00:36:01.879 --> 00:36:05.199
involves a separate server and a client.

00:36:05.199 --> 00:36:09.159
And we've mentioned the word server several times today,

00:36:09.159 --> 00:36:11.360
but essentially a server is a machine

00:36:11.360 --> 00:36:13.120
that's connected to the internet

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:16.879
that runs 24 seven ready to run your Shiny app.

00:36:16.879 --> 00:36:21.879
And the server runs R or Python and Shiny,

00:36:21.959 --> 00:36:25.280
and clients connect via the web browser.

00:36:25.280 --> 00:36:28.840
And each client keeps an open web socket connection

00:36:28.840 --> 00:36:31.280
as long as they are using the application.

00:36:31.280 --> 00:36:35.800
So this is like probably the simplest way that this works.

00:36:35.800 --> 00:36:37.520
There are more complex setups,

00:36:37.520 --> 00:36:40.239
but fundamentally this is kind of what it looks like.

00:36:42.560 --> 00:36:44.399
And in terms of hosting Shiny apps,

00:36:44.399 --> 00:36:46.280
there are a lot of different options

00:36:46.280 --> 00:36:48.239
for hosting your server.

00:36:48.239 --> 00:36:52.399
So for example, you can have RStudio server on your laptop

00:36:52.399 --> 00:36:54.399
and say you need some scalability

00:36:54.399 --> 00:36:56.520
or additional security for your app,

00:36:56.520 --> 00:36:58.760
you can get Posit Connect,

00:36:58.760 --> 00:37:01.719
which is an enterprise version from Posit

00:37:01.719 --> 00:37:06.080
and for hosting your Shiny apps.

00:37:06.080 --> 00:37:08.639
There are also cloud-based solutions.

00:37:08.639 --> 00:37:12.919
Shinyapps.io has been around for a long time.

00:37:12.919 --> 00:37:16.399
There is a new product called Posit Connect Cloud

00:37:16.399 --> 00:37:18.840
that lets you publish Shiny

00:37:18.840 --> 00:37:23.840
and also all sorts of kind of Python frameworks as well.

00:37:24.239 --> 00:37:27.840
And then like things like Hugging Face,

00:37:27.840 --> 00:37:30.879
you can roll your own if you would like.

00:37:30.879 --> 00:37:34.479
And then in terms of choosing what the right tool is,

00:37:34.479 --> 00:37:36.399
it's a very wide spectrum

00:37:36.399 --> 00:37:38.399
in terms of the number of users.

00:37:38.399 --> 00:37:40.919
For some people, we might just be sharing our apps

00:37:40.919 --> 00:37:42.959
with one or two other people.

00:37:42.959 --> 00:37:45.840
For other people, we might be talking thousands.

00:37:45.840 --> 00:37:47.560
And then there are some folks in between,

00:37:47.560 --> 00:37:50.360
like a professor, an academic,

00:37:50.360 --> 00:37:53.399
might have a few hundred folks looking at their apps.

00:37:53.399 --> 00:37:56.000
But what if you don't have the infrastructure

00:37:56.000 --> 00:38:01.000
or the resources to set up either of these kind of options?

00:38:03.600 --> 00:38:07.159
Another kind of hosting service are web hosting services.

00:38:07.159 --> 00:38:10.560
And they offer a lot of scalability and features

00:38:10.560 --> 00:38:14.600
and perhaps a low price point,

00:38:14.600 --> 00:38:17.919
like GitHub Pages or Netlify or Ordo Pub,

00:38:17.919 --> 00:38:21.199
but the issue is they can't run traditional Shiny apps.

00:38:21.199 --> 00:38:24.600
And the reason is that these are called static web hosting.

00:38:24.600 --> 00:38:27.600
They're very good in terms of reach and affordability.

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:30.760
You don't have to think about servers anymore.

00:38:30.760 --> 00:38:33.120
So when you publish, say, a quarter website,

00:38:33.120 --> 00:38:38.120
you just give them your rendered Porto document files.

00:38:38.199 --> 00:38:41.520
But there is no way to run Shiny apps

00:38:41.520 --> 00:38:43.080
on these kind of servers,

00:38:43.080 --> 00:38:46.360
on these kind of web hosting services.

00:38:46.360 --> 00:38:50.040
So if you've ever created a Shiny app before

00:38:50.040 --> 00:38:52.479
and you've wanted to share it via a website,

00:38:52.479 --> 00:38:55.760
you've probably had to embed it in an iframe

00:38:55.760 --> 00:38:58.760
when you wanted to share it.

00:38:58.760 --> 00:39:02.399
But that is not the only option anymore.

00:39:02.399 --> 00:39:04.479
Thanks to Shiny Live,

00:39:04.479 --> 00:39:07.439
anybody can create their own serverless Shiny apps

00:39:07.439 --> 00:39:10.760
to run in the browser.

00:39:10.760 --> 00:39:12.320
And in terms of what this looks like,

00:39:12.320 --> 00:39:15.280
here is a very simple Shiny app.

00:39:15.280 --> 00:39:19.000
And remember, this is a portal presentation,

00:39:19.000 --> 00:39:20.840
and this is not an iframe.

00:39:20.840 --> 00:39:23.919
This is embedded in the presentation itself.

00:39:23.919 --> 00:39:26.040
And this is a Shiny app.

00:39:26.040 --> 00:39:27.840
So I could change the number,

00:39:27.840 --> 00:39:29.919
I can change the color,

00:39:29.919 --> 00:39:34.919
and did not have to host this

00:39:35.239 --> 00:39:37.600
on any kind of external server.

00:39:37.600 --> 00:39:40.879
All it is, it's on the web.

00:39:42.639 --> 00:39:46.320
So, I'm sorry.

00:39:46.320 --> 00:39:50.280
Yes, Shiny Live was announced in July 2022 for Python,

00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:52.560
September 2023 for R.

00:39:52.560 --> 00:39:55.159
And it uses PyDyed and WebR respectively

00:39:55.159 --> 00:39:59.760
to enable fully in-browser Shiny apps without a backend.

00:39:59.760 --> 00:40:03.520
And so, in terms of the architecture,

00:40:03.520 --> 00:40:08.040
all you need to run Shiny Live is these static web servers.

00:40:08.040 --> 00:40:11.120
So when an application is deployed with Shiny Live,

00:40:11.120 --> 00:40:14.159
R or Python and Shiny run in the web browser,

00:40:14.159 --> 00:40:16.919
the browser is effectively both the client

00:40:16.919 --> 00:40:19.479
and the server for the application.

00:40:19.479 --> 00:40:21.959
And that is pretty amazing.

00:40:21.959 --> 00:40:25.600
So you don't need a separate server to host these apps.

00:40:27.479 --> 00:40:30.840
In terms of how to use Shiny Live, you have three options.

00:40:30.840 --> 00:40:33.840
One is the Shiny Live online editor.

00:40:33.840 --> 00:40:35.760
The second is you can convert a Shiny app

00:40:35.760 --> 00:40:38.360
that you've created traditionally.

00:40:38.360 --> 00:40:41.560
And the third is you can embed a Shiny app with Cordo.

00:40:42.560 --> 00:40:47.080
So there is an online Shiny Live editor for R and for Python.

00:40:47.080 --> 00:40:48.639
So let's open this up.

00:40:50.360 --> 00:40:52.159
The editor is on the left

00:40:52.159 --> 00:40:55.000
and you can change this app in real time.

00:40:55.000 --> 00:40:56.439
So let's let it load.

00:40:57.360 --> 00:40:59.360
There are several examples here,

00:40:59.360 --> 00:41:02.639
which is very helpful if you are new to Shiny

00:41:02.639 --> 00:41:04.879
and you want to see what it looks like

00:41:04.879 --> 00:41:07.040
and you want to play around with it.

00:41:07.040 --> 00:41:10.080
Here's the editor and then here is the app.

00:41:10.879 --> 00:41:12.320
And it's a real app.

00:41:12.320 --> 00:41:13.840
I can change this.

00:41:13.840 --> 00:41:15.280
Number of bins change.

00:41:16.159 --> 00:41:20.080
Similarly, I can change, say, the number of bins.

00:41:20.080 --> 00:41:21.959
I want the max to be 500.

00:41:22.879 --> 00:41:24.600
I can rerun the app.

00:41:25.679 --> 00:41:29.520
And then this, instead of 50, now it's 500.

00:41:29.520 --> 00:41:32.520
And again, I can move it around and change it.

00:41:32.520 --> 00:41:34.199
If I were to take this code,

00:41:34.199 --> 00:41:37.679
say I copy and pasted it into RStudio,

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:41.520
as long as I have all the packages installed, it would run.

00:41:41.520 --> 00:41:44.959
And then I would see this in my viewer pane, for example.

00:41:44.959 --> 00:41:48.000
And it, again, is one of the ways

00:41:48.000 --> 00:41:51.560
that you can create a Shiny Live app.

00:41:51.560 --> 00:41:55.239
In terms of sharing, up here there is a share button

00:41:55.239 --> 00:41:58.560
and there are actually a couple of options you can use.

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:00.600
So say you are working with somebody

00:42:00.600 --> 00:42:02.919
who already knows R or Python

00:42:02.919 --> 00:42:05.439
and you want them to work on that same app,

00:42:05.439 --> 00:42:07.239
you could do it with an editor URL.

00:42:07.760 --> 00:42:09.040
So it'd look kind of like this.

00:42:09.040 --> 00:42:12.919
Or say you just want to show it and not allow them to edit,

00:42:12.919 --> 00:42:16.439
you can share the application URL.

00:42:16.439 --> 00:42:18.159
You notice it's very long.

00:42:18.159 --> 00:42:20.800
It's because it contains all the information

00:42:20.800 --> 00:42:24.959
that is needed in order to create this app on the web,

00:42:24.959 --> 00:42:26.560
but it's completely shareable.

00:42:26.560 --> 00:42:28.959
If I sent this to you, you would open it up,

00:42:28.959 --> 00:42:31.360
say, let's look good at what this looks like,

00:42:32.800 --> 00:42:34.320
and it would look like this.

00:42:34.320 --> 00:42:36.800
And then it would load on your browser

00:42:37.360 --> 00:42:38.800
and you can edit the code

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:42.239
and you can play around with the app or anything like that.

00:42:44.000 --> 00:42:46.159
Something else I wanted to know is,

00:42:46.159 --> 00:42:48.959
I saw this question on Blue Sky recently,

00:42:48.959 --> 00:42:53.959
was should I be using BSLib for creating Shiny apps?

00:42:53.959 --> 00:42:57.320
And if you have not heard of BSLib before,

00:42:57.320 --> 00:43:01.800
BSLib is kind of like the next generation package

00:43:01.800 --> 00:43:04.239
for Shiny creation and styling.

00:43:04.239 --> 00:43:07.199
And it aims to make these beautiful looking apps

00:43:07.199 --> 00:43:08.239
right out of the box.

00:43:08.239 --> 00:43:10.719
So if you've ever heard somebody say like,

00:43:10.719 --> 00:43:12.360
oh, it looks like a Shiny app

00:43:12.360 --> 00:43:14.479
and it needs customization and stuff like that,

00:43:14.479 --> 00:43:17.120
BSLib aims to make it look pretty stunning

00:43:17.120 --> 00:43:17.959
right off the bat.

00:43:17.959 --> 00:43:20.320
So all of these are done with BSLib.

00:43:20.320 --> 00:43:23.399
And so this is also a really great opportunity

00:43:23.399 --> 00:43:25.000
that if you are new to BSLib,

00:43:25.000 --> 00:43:28.040
you can kind of see how things are different,

00:43:28.040 --> 00:43:30.560
how the layout is structured and things like that.

00:43:31.520 --> 00:43:34.959
And there's a ton of kind of example texts

00:43:34.959 --> 00:43:36.320
if you wanna try it out.

00:43:42.199 --> 00:43:44.360
Going back to our presentation.

00:43:46.919 --> 00:43:50.120
So the first option was to use the Shiny Live Online Editor.

00:43:50.120 --> 00:43:52.199
The second is you can convert a Shiny app

00:43:52.199 --> 00:43:53.679
that you've already written.

00:43:53.679 --> 00:43:58.679
So if you did a dashboard with Shiny for R

00:43:58.679 --> 00:44:00.760
or Shiny for Python,

00:44:00.760 --> 00:44:03.560
then you install the Shiny Live package.

00:44:04.679 --> 00:44:06.360
Then you can export the app.

00:44:06.360 --> 00:44:09.679
So we're using the export function.

00:44:09.679 --> 00:44:14.439
And this converts the app into a My App directory

00:44:14.439 --> 00:44:17.040
and produces an output directory site.

00:44:17.040 --> 00:44:18.919
And it will give you all the files

00:44:18.919 --> 00:44:22.120
that you would need to give to a static web hosting service

00:44:22.120 --> 00:44:24.080
in order to see your app.

00:44:25.080 --> 00:44:28.639
And if you want to, you can also preview the app

00:44:28.639 --> 00:44:31.719
by running this run static server function.

00:44:31.719 --> 00:44:34.679
And then it will open up in a web browser.

00:44:34.679 --> 00:44:39.679
So if you prefer to do something like on our studio desktop

00:44:41.399 --> 00:44:42.560
or something like that,

00:44:42.560 --> 00:44:45.159
and then you want to convert it

00:44:45.159 --> 00:44:47.239
so that you can put it up on the web somewhere,

00:44:47.239 --> 00:44:48.639
this is an option for you.

00:44:49.239 --> 00:44:52.439
And then the final way that you can create

00:44:52.439 --> 00:44:54.000
and share Shiny Live apps

00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:57.080
is using the Shiny Live extension.

00:44:57.080 --> 00:44:59.719
So you install the Cordo extension.

00:44:59.719 --> 00:45:02.560
Again, it should look a little familiar.

00:45:02.560 --> 00:45:05.439
And then you add it to your Cordo document YAML heading

00:45:05.439 --> 00:45:06.760
under filters.

00:45:10.479 --> 00:45:12.639
And then within your Cordo document,

00:45:12.639 --> 00:45:16.080
you insert a code block with either Shiny Live Python

00:45:16.080 --> 00:45:17.800
or Shiny Live Python.

00:45:18.159 --> 00:45:20.199
Or Shiny Live R.

00:45:20.199 --> 00:45:21.040
And that's it.

00:45:21.040 --> 00:45:24.840
So like that app that you saw a little bit earlier,

00:45:24.840 --> 00:45:27.439
this is similar to the code chunk

00:45:27.439 --> 00:45:29.560
that I put in my presentation

00:45:29.560 --> 00:45:33.120
in order to create a Shiny Live application

00:45:33.120 --> 00:45:34.919
that I could edit in real time.

00:45:37.439 --> 00:45:38.479
A few examples.

00:45:38.479 --> 00:45:41.000
So one is the Shiny for Python docs.

00:45:41.679 --> 00:45:46.679
So this is an example of embedding interactiveness

00:45:46.679 --> 00:45:50.280
in documentation so that people can learn

00:45:50.280 --> 00:45:52.959
and pick up and iterate just in real time

00:45:52.959 --> 00:45:56.600
without having to set anything up on their own end.

00:45:56.600 --> 00:46:01.600
So here is an example with the app.py.

00:46:02.159 --> 00:46:04.439
You can play around with it and say,

00:46:04.439 --> 00:46:06.679
I'm new to this, I can start messing around

00:46:06.679 --> 00:46:10.080
and seeing how things change every time I do this.

00:46:10.080 --> 00:46:12.919
How things change every time I rerun the app.

00:46:13.919 --> 00:46:16.879
There are things like the components.

00:46:18.919 --> 00:46:21.280
And I mentioned earlier, you know,

00:46:21.280 --> 00:46:25.360
be a sliv, like say you want to see what a layout looks like

00:46:25.360 --> 00:46:26.840
by changing things up.

00:46:26.840 --> 00:46:29.600
You can change it in the app right there, right then.

00:46:33.320 --> 00:46:36.560
Another example, again from Classability,

00:46:36.560 --> 00:46:39.760
is this color picker app.

00:46:40.439 --> 00:46:43.520
It's just another example of a Shiny Live app

00:46:43.520 --> 00:46:46.679
that's done, that's shared in the browser.

00:46:46.679 --> 00:46:49.280
So it's shareable through this URL

00:46:49.280 --> 00:46:52.040
and no server required.

00:46:52.040 --> 00:46:55.520
So say, you know, this professor has hundreds of students,

00:46:55.520 --> 00:47:00.520
not enough bandwidth on shinyapps.io to host the Shiny app,

00:47:00.600 --> 00:47:04.159
but on a web browser, it's absolutely doable.

00:47:04.159 --> 00:47:07.679
And then it's also an example of a more complex example

00:47:07.679 --> 00:47:09.080
of a Shiny app.

00:47:09.120 --> 00:47:12.239
So really, even though it is like more complex

00:47:12.239 --> 00:47:14.719
and it's doing a lot in the backend and things like that,

00:47:14.719 --> 00:47:16.959
it's still runnable in the browser.

00:47:20.280 --> 00:47:23.080
And the final example that I want to show

00:47:23.080 --> 00:47:24.360
is Shiny Assistant.

00:47:24.360 --> 00:47:28.239
So with the admin of AI, there's so many different ways

00:47:28.239 --> 00:47:31.199
of embedding AI into tools.

00:47:31.199 --> 00:47:36.199
And this one embeds AI for R or Python

00:47:36.800 --> 00:47:41.120
through the Elmer package for R or chat list for Python

00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:44.360
and with Shiny Live to create a Shiny Assistant.

00:47:44.360 --> 00:47:47.360
So this is a chat bot and you can see it says,

00:47:47.360 --> 00:47:49.199
hello, I'm Shiny Assistant.

00:47:49.199 --> 00:47:50.679
I'm here to help you with Shiny.

00:47:50.679 --> 00:47:52.679
Gives you some examples.

00:47:52.679 --> 00:47:55.719
And because it's Shiny Live, again,

00:47:55.719 --> 00:47:58.679
completely on the browser, and I can say,

00:47:58.679 --> 00:48:03.679
could you help me make a really simple Shiny app?

00:48:06.959 --> 00:48:11.959
And then the editor and the app shows up

00:48:12.320 --> 00:48:13.879
here on the right-hand side.

00:48:13.879 --> 00:48:17.239
And so like the docs or examples that you saw earlier,

00:48:17.239 --> 00:48:20.520
this is totally editable.

00:48:20.520 --> 00:48:24.840
This is absolutely runnable and say,

00:48:24.840 --> 00:48:26.800
and because this is a chat bot too,

00:48:26.800 --> 00:48:28.760
I can go back and forth.

00:48:28.760 --> 00:48:33.760
And so I can say, could you add another visualization

00:48:36.199 --> 00:48:37.040
please?

00:48:38.439 --> 00:48:43.320
And here on the left, it's going to generate the code.

00:48:43.320 --> 00:48:45.800
It's going to talk about what it's done.

00:48:45.800 --> 00:48:49.159
It updates the editor and the app as well.

00:48:49.159 --> 00:48:51.120
And so as you can imagine,

00:48:51.120 --> 00:48:54.399
this is a really great way of building prototypes.

00:48:54.399 --> 00:48:57.840
So BSLib is a really great way of getting started,

00:48:57.840 --> 00:49:01.439
but say you have a specific layout in mind

00:49:01.439 --> 00:49:02.719
or something like that,

00:49:02.719 --> 00:49:05.399
and you don't want to forget a parentheses

00:49:05.399 --> 00:49:06.280
or something like that.

00:49:06.280 --> 00:49:09.000
You can work with Shiny Assistant to create the prototype

00:49:09.000 --> 00:49:13.040
of what it is that you want and get it set up there.

00:49:13.040 --> 00:49:16.399
Like before, you can share it so that, you know,

00:49:16.399 --> 00:49:19.000
somebody can give you feedback or things like that,

00:49:19.000 --> 00:49:20.479
or say that you've gotten to the point

00:49:20.479 --> 00:49:23.399
that you don't want to say upload

00:49:23.399 --> 00:49:25.439
your sensitive data up here, right?

00:49:25.439 --> 00:49:27.040
Because this is the web.

00:49:27.040 --> 00:49:29.800
And so instead of what you can do

00:49:29.800 --> 00:49:31.840
is you can download the project files

00:49:31.840 --> 00:49:35.120
and then open it up in the editor of your choice

00:49:35.120 --> 00:49:37.840
so that you can make further modifications

00:49:37.840 --> 00:49:41.639
and build the exact app with the data that you need.

00:49:41.639 --> 00:49:45.919
But this is, again, possible thanks to Shiny Live

00:49:45.919 --> 00:49:49.879
and all the advancements that there've been in AI

00:49:49.879 --> 00:49:53.399
and the integration of AI into different tools.

00:49:53.399 --> 00:49:56.040
And so if you haven't played around with Shiny Assistant,

00:49:56.040 --> 00:49:57.719
I highly recommend it.

00:49:57.719 --> 00:50:00.719
It is how I start with almost every single one

00:50:00.719 --> 00:50:02.159
of my Shiny apps now.

00:50:08.320 --> 00:50:11.560
Okay, so with that, let's talk about some use cases.

00:50:11.560 --> 00:50:14.600
We've talked a lot about the technology

00:50:14.600 --> 00:50:16.760
and possibilities and things like that.

00:50:16.760 --> 00:50:18.800
So let's just kind of outline them.

00:50:18.800 --> 00:50:23.360
So first of all, it's sharing interactive reports

00:50:23.360 --> 00:50:25.159
and dashboards with executable code.

00:50:25.159 --> 00:50:29.919
So with WebR and Pyodaj, Border Live, Shiny Live,

00:50:29.919 --> 00:50:34.520
it provides a smooth, interactive, immediate introduction

00:50:34.520 --> 00:50:36.840
to the world of working with data.

00:50:36.840 --> 00:50:40.600
So users who haven't had the chance to use R

00:50:40.600 --> 00:50:44.639
due to barriers, but because of software installation

00:50:44.639 --> 00:50:46.919
or cloud-based service registrations

00:50:46.919 --> 00:50:50.320
or anything like that can be introduced to R and Python

00:50:50.320 --> 00:50:52.639
thanks to these interactive examples.

00:50:54.040 --> 00:50:58.600
You can also create reproducible documentation

00:50:58.600 --> 00:51:00.320
through containerization

00:51:00.320 --> 00:51:02.679
and notebook-style literate programming.

00:51:03.800 --> 00:51:08.840
And linked here is a article to a Nature post

00:51:08.840 --> 00:51:12.879
about how WebAssembly is changing how research is shared.

00:51:15.239 --> 00:51:18.000
The R Consortium Submissions Group

00:51:18.000 --> 00:51:21.320
is a group that is working on improved practices

00:51:21.320 --> 00:51:24.360
of R in clinical trial research.

00:51:24.360 --> 00:51:25.800
And thanks to Shiny Live,

00:51:25.800 --> 00:51:29.120
they have successfully submitted a pilot R Shiny app

00:51:29.120 --> 00:51:32.520
featuring Shiny Live to the FDA for review.

00:51:35.320 --> 00:51:37.760
And in terms of educational benefits,

00:51:37.760 --> 00:51:40.800
again, say you're doing an intro to R Workshop,

00:51:40.800 --> 00:51:44.040
you can dive into the code without any software.

00:51:44.040 --> 00:51:46.679
You can remix examples on the fly.

00:51:46.679 --> 00:51:50.239
You can have this kind of tactile educational content

00:51:50.239 --> 00:51:54.000
with interactive experimentation for your students.

00:51:54.000 --> 00:51:56.199
There's reduced context switching,

00:51:56.199 --> 00:51:58.639
so they don't have to switch between the console

00:51:58.639 --> 00:52:01.879
and the tutorial, all in all making the learning process

00:52:01.879 --> 00:52:04.280
more streamlined and engaging.

00:52:04.280 --> 00:52:08.360
And then for professors who want to service apps

00:52:08.360 --> 00:52:09.399
for hundreds of people,

00:52:09.399 --> 00:52:12.399
but don't have the computational load available to them,

00:52:12.399 --> 00:52:14.479
this is another use case.

00:52:17.000 --> 00:52:20.760
In terms of benefits, this idea of sharing easily,

00:52:20.760 --> 00:52:23.439
so it shines in accessibility,

00:52:23.439 --> 00:52:24.959
your content can be hosted

00:52:24.959 --> 00:52:27.439
on any static web hosting service

00:52:27.439 --> 00:52:31.439
and you can share it with just a URL.

00:52:31.439 --> 00:52:35.320
Users can run code without installing software.

00:52:35.320 --> 00:52:40.320
It can be run on any device or like tablets or mobile.

00:52:40.320 --> 00:52:43.080
If you haven't seen ThinkR's R Lingo,

00:52:43.080 --> 00:52:45.520
it's a mobile way of working with R,

00:52:45.520 --> 00:52:48.120
so if you really want to work with R on your phone.

00:52:49.120 --> 00:52:49.959
Oops.

00:52:51.560 --> 00:52:52.520
Okay, so that's it.

00:52:55.239 --> 00:52:57.439
But there are things to consider

00:52:57.439 --> 00:53:01.280
and very important kind of decisions

00:53:01.280 --> 00:53:02.840
that you have to make before deciding

00:53:02.840 --> 00:53:05.959
on whether you're gonna use Corda Live and Shiny Live.

00:53:05.959 --> 00:53:09.120
So first thing is that it's under active development

00:53:09.120 --> 00:53:10.479
and things might change.

00:53:11.879 --> 00:53:14.679
Some packages are not supported yet.

00:53:15.679 --> 00:53:19.159
And depending on network access, some might just not work.

00:53:20.560 --> 00:53:22.199
Probably most importantly,

00:53:22.199 --> 00:53:24.120
maybe should have had this as a first bullet,

00:53:24.120 --> 00:53:26.560
is there are no secrets to the Shiny Live apps

00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:28.919
that's George Stagg.

00:53:28.919 --> 00:53:31.280
So all the source code goes to the client,

00:53:31.280 --> 00:53:33.520
all the data goes to the client.

00:53:33.520 --> 00:53:36.159
And so because everything runs client-side,

00:53:36.159 --> 00:53:38.800
you want to be careful what you use it for.

00:53:38.800 --> 00:53:42.000
So be sure to never include credentials,

00:53:42.000 --> 00:53:44.199
be sure to never include sensors,

00:53:44.600 --> 00:53:46.600
and never include sensitive data.

00:53:48.399 --> 00:53:51.320
And finally, for large data sets, large packages,

00:53:51.320 --> 00:53:53.280
or really intensive tasks,

00:53:53.280 --> 00:53:56.399
you want to be cognizant of the performance limitations

00:53:56.399 --> 00:53:57.639
that might exist.

00:53:57.639 --> 00:53:59.719
It might just be really, really slow

00:53:59.719 --> 00:54:02.639
and therefore unusable to some of your audience.

00:54:05.000 --> 00:54:07.000
So to sum up a few best practices,

00:54:07.000 --> 00:54:09.560
you want to keep the computations lightweight

00:54:09.560 --> 00:54:11.320
and structure code efficiently.

00:54:11.320 --> 00:54:14.040
You want to offset these kind of performance limitations

00:54:14.040 --> 00:54:15.919
that could exist.

00:54:15.919 --> 00:54:19.159
You want to make sure to manage your dependencies correctly.

00:54:19.159 --> 00:54:20.399
But really, ultimately,

00:54:20.399 --> 00:54:22.800
it's about choosing the right tool for the job.

00:54:22.800 --> 00:54:26.439
You know your work best, you know your data best.

00:54:26.439 --> 00:54:30.120
There might be times where, again, Shiny Assistant

00:54:30.120 --> 00:54:33.560
is a great time for prototyping and things like that.

00:54:33.560 --> 00:54:35.639
But if you have a data set with real names,

00:54:35.639 --> 00:54:36.840
that's when you download it

00:54:36.840 --> 00:54:40.239
and pull it into something that's nice and secure

00:54:40.239 --> 00:54:41.280
and airtight.

00:54:42.280 --> 00:54:45.959
But if it is something like you're creating exercises,

00:54:45.959 --> 00:54:48.879
you want to show off some cool functions in a blog post,

00:54:48.879 --> 00:54:50.520
it might be the right tool,

00:54:50.520 --> 00:54:53.159
and that is up to you to decide.

00:54:54.879 --> 00:54:57.919
So really, it's a very exciting time.

00:54:57.919 --> 00:55:00.399
I hope that you're excited, too,

00:55:00.399 --> 00:55:02.479
and have learned some new things today

00:55:02.479 --> 00:55:05.239
in terms of the future of interactive data science.

00:55:05.239 --> 00:55:08.760
As Joe Chang said when he announced

00:55:08.760 --> 00:55:11.199
Shiny Live for R at PositConf,

00:55:11.199 --> 00:55:13.959
truly is we're exploring a new frontier.

00:55:13.959 --> 00:55:17.000
And there are so many options that you can do

00:55:17.000 --> 00:55:21.800
in order to leverage these tools in new formats.

00:55:21.800 --> 00:55:24.800
And these are just examples that I came up with,

00:55:24.800 --> 00:55:26.800
but I'm sure there's so many other options

00:55:26.800 --> 00:55:30.080
that I cannot even dream of.

00:55:30.080 --> 00:55:31.800
And so I'm really excited to see

00:55:31.800 --> 00:55:34.159
how you take it and run with it.

00:55:35.520 --> 00:55:37.600
And with that, thank you.

00:55:37.600 --> 00:55:38.959
Very open to any questions,

00:55:38.959 --> 00:55:41.719
and thank you again for joining me.

00:55:46.520 --> 00:55:48.199
Thank you very much, Isabella.

