Okay, but I asked the audience

00:56:05.600 --> 00:56:08.560
if you'd like to ask a question directly to Isabella,

00:56:08.560 --> 00:56:10.320
please raise your hand.

00:56:11.199 --> 00:56:14.239
While I'm reading these questions

00:56:14.239 --> 00:56:16.399
that I've read along the way.

00:56:16.399 --> 00:56:18.080
So the first one was,

00:56:18.080 --> 00:56:21.479
is there a way to log in and set up an account

00:56:21.479 --> 00:56:26.479
for the web, so the use of R in the browser?

00:56:27.320 --> 00:56:32.320
Hmm, so let me know if I'm answering this correctly.

00:56:33.439 --> 00:56:34.360
You don't need to log in

00:56:34.360 --> 00:56:37.520
if you want to set up an account to use WebR,

00:56:37.520 --> 00:56:39.760
you have to install the packages.

00:56:39.760 --> 00:56:43.479
And again, you have like the JavaScript kind of option

00:56:43.479 --> 00:56:44.840
if you know JavaScript,

00:56:44.840 --> 00:56:48.080
or you have Cordo documents if you want to use that.

00:56:48.080 --> 00:56:50.239
So all of that, you don't require a login

00:56:50.239 --> 00:56:51.719
or anything like that.

00:56:51.719 --> 00:56:53.520
If the question is like,

00:56:53.520 --> 00:56:57.439
can you set up say a Cordo document with a login

00:56:57.439 --> 00:57:00.600
to a document with WebR chunks?

00:57:00.600 --> 00:57:02.439
I believe that is possible.

00:57:02.439 --> 00:57:06.000
But again, just remember once,

00:57:06.000 --> 00:57:08.280
you know, somebody gets past that login,

00:57:08.280 --> 00:57:10.679
all those WebR chunks are still on the web

00:57:10.679 --> 00:57:11.719
and everything like that.

00:57:11.719 --> 00:57:14.199
So if it is something that you want

00:57:14.199 --> 00:57:18.560
to really keep secret or private or anything like that,

00:57:18.600 --> 00:57:21.600
that you might want to consider some other options.

00:57:23.439 --> 00:57:28.439
Okay, so that answers the second question as well.

00:57:29.840 --> 00:57:33.439
The third one was, does Cordo offer advantages

00:57:33.439 --> 00:57:36.719
over using Jupyter Notebook for publishing?

00:57:37.639 --> 00:57:42.159
Yeah, so I would say, so one advantage, for example,

00:57:42.159 --> 00:57:43.520
is the one that you saw today.

00:57:43.520 --> 00:57:46.000
So thanks to the Jupyter Notebook,

00:57:46.199 --> 00:57:47.800
the one that you saw today.

00:57:47.800 --> 00:57:52.800
So thanks to the massive universe of extensions

00:57:53.040 --> 00:57:55.280
that Cordo offers, there are so many things

00:57:55.280 --> 00:57:57.479
that you could do with Cordo documents

00:57:57.479 --> 00:57:59.919
that are not possible in Jupyter Notebooks.

00:57:59.919 --> 00:58:01.479
So if you want to create a document

00:58:01.479 --> 00:58:03.719
with interactive chunks,

00:58:03.719 --> 00:58:05.639
you might be able to do that with Pyedide,

00:58:05.639 --> 00:58:07.760
but not if you're an R user.

00:58:08.959 --> 00:58:12.760
And in terms of other kind of advantages,

00:58:12.760 --> 00:58:15.239
I would say like there's the multilingual aspect.

00:58:15.280 --> 00:58:19.360
Again, if you are an R and a Python user,

00:58:19.360 --> 00:58:22.679
you don't have to switch contexts so much

00:58:22.679 --> 00:58:26.840
to be able to use like different kind of tools.

00:58:26.840 --> 00:58:29.479
I personally think that Cordo documents

00:58:29.479 --> 00:58:33.560
are much more readable and user-friendly to use,

00:58:33.560 --> 00:58:35.239
especially since Jupyter Notebooks

00:58:35.239 --> 00:58:37.800
have kind of that JSON backend

00:58:37.800 --> 00:58:40.639
that can be kind of tricky with version control.

00:58:40.639 --> 00:58:43.000
Cordo, since it's markdown-based,

00:58:43.000 --> 00:58:45.679
doesn't run into those kinds of issues.

00:58:45.679 --> 00:58:49.760
And finally, I really like the outputs that Cordo creates.

00:58:49.760 --> 00:58:51.840
So like the slides that you see here,

00:58:51.840 --> 00:58:53.520
the websites, the blogs,

00:58:53.520 --> 00:58:55.479
I just think they look really nice.

00:58:55.479 --> 00:58:59.679
And I think like there is a huge advantage

00:58:59.679 --> 00:59:03.199
to be able to present things that look professional

00:59:03.199 --> 00:59:04.919
and crisp and clear.

00:59:04.919 --> 00:59:06.959
And I think Cordo really excels in that.

00:59:14.000 --> 00:59:15.479
Oop, I think you're unmuted.

00:59:17.560 --> 00:59:18.399
Oh, sorry.

00:59:19.719 --> 00:59:21.840
Yeah, thank you for answering the question.

