So that was interesting to me as well.

00:59:24.159 --> 00:59:28.320
So I wanted to, there's a full question that says,

00:59:28.320 --> 00:59:31.080
how would you share your R document

00:59:31.080 --> 00:59:34.080
with say someone who does not have R?

00:59:35.959 --> 00:59:37.399
Yeah, so for example,

00:59:37.399 --> 00:59:41.760
if you create a Cordo document with R,

00:59:42.320 --> 00:59:44.919
code chunks, what you would do is you would share,

00:59:44.919 --> 00:59:49.320
like you would publish that document to say GitHub pages,

00:59:49.320 --> 00:59:53.320
to Netlify, to some sort of web host server,

00:59:53.320 --> 00:59:55.399
and then you just share a URL.

00:59:55.399 --> 00:59:58.719
And so, you know, if I were to share like my blog post,

00:59:58.719 --> 01:00:01.280
for example, all of that is R.

01:00:01.280 --> 01:00:05.080
And even if somebody's computer doesn't have R installed

01:00:06.040 --> 01:00:09.560
or RStudio installed or any kind of editor installed,

01:00:09.560 --> 01:00:12.479
all they need is a browser and an internet connection,

01:00:12.479 --> 01:00:14.159
and then they can run R code.

