Then we have other two questions.

01:00:18.280 --> 01:00:22.520
I don't know if Eva would like to ask herself.

01:00:24.639 --> 01:00:27.360
You want to ask directly to Isabella maybe?

01:00:27.360 --> 01:00:28.800
You can unmute yourself.

01:00:30.280 --> 01:00:31.120
Can you?

01:00:33.320 --> 01:00:34.560
Yes, thank you.

01:00:36.040 --> 01:00:39.120
So I'm working on a dashboard

01:00:39.679 --> 01:00:41.360
and some of it is static.

01:00:41.360 --> 01:00:45.879
And now I would like to have interactive part to it.

01:00:45.879 --> 01:00:48.120
And I was trying ShinyLive already.

01:00:48.120 --> 01:00:52.560
And is it possible, let's say I prepared the data,

01:00:52.560 --> 01:00:55.520
I filtered, I added some calculations,

01:00:55.520 --> 01:00:59.239
and then I want to have, let's say, interactive plot.

01:00:59.239 --> 01:01:04.239
Can I communicate from within my R chunks

01:01:04.520 --> 01:01:07.000
to ShinyLive chunk,

01:01:07.080 --> 01:01:09.879
or does the whole thing have to be ShinyLive?

01:01:11.040 --> 01:01:13.679
Yeah, so I would say you have two options.

01:01:13.679 --> 01:01:15.879
Since they started with a Cordo dashboard,

01:01:15.879 --> 01:01:18.639
Cordo dashboards actually do allow

01:01:18.639 --> 01:01:20.719
using of Shiny components.

01:01:20.719 --> 01:01:23.320
So say you want to add a sidebar

01:01:23.320 --> 01:01:26.600
where people toggle between different colors

01:01:26.600 --> 01:01:28.520
in their plot or something like that,

01:01:28.520 --> 01:01:30.639
that Cordo can absolutely do that.

01:01:30.639 --> 01:01:34.800
It is kind of in like Shiny syntax.

01:01:34.800 --> 01:01:37.320
You have to be like, you know,

01:01:37.320 --> 01:01:40.120
you need to be familiar with that and things like that.

01:01:40.120 --> 01:01:45.040
But the Cordo dashboard guide on the Cordo documentation

01:01:45.040 --> 01:01:46.840
kind of shows some examples.

01:01:46.840 --> 01:01:49.479
And there's also a dashboard gallery with some,

01:01:49.479 --> 01:01:50.760
you know, if you want to pull them up

01:01:50.760 --> 01:01:53.159
and see their source code and see how they did it.

01:01:53.159 --> 01:01:54.360
So that's one thing.

01:01:54.360 --> 01:01:57.280
It's Cordo dashboards with Shiny components.

01:01:58.159 --> 01:02:01.600
And then the other option is to create a Shiny app

01:02:01.600 --> 01:02:04.399
that's hosted on, you know,

01:02:04.399 --> 01:02:08.439
that is either ShinyLive or a traditional Shiny app.

01:02:08.439 --> 01:02:11.800
And I think like in terms of the consideration

01:02:11.800 --> 01:02:13.719
of like, which one do you choose?

01:02:13.719 --> 01:02:15.199
It's one of those things that, again,

01:02:15.199 --> 01:02:18.120
it depends on you and your data and your audience

01:02:18.120 --> 01:02:23.120
and, you know, the resources that you have available.

01:02:23.320 --> 01:02:26.639
If you don't want to start all over from scratch,

01:02:26.639 --> 01:02:28.199
I would say like, you know,

01:02:28.199 --> 01:02:30.760
try out the Shiny components in the Cordo dashboard

01:02:30.760 --> 01:02:32.800
and see what that's like.

01:02:32.800 --> 01:02:35.080
Or another option is if you want to try it

01:02:35.080 --> 01:02:37.479
is to ask the Shiny assistant, right?

01:02:37.479 --> 01:02:39.560
Like I'm creating this app or dashboard,

01:02:39.560 --> 01:02:42.679
can you, you know, help me convert it to Shiny code

01:02:42.679 --> 01:02:44.320
and see how it goes?

01:02:44.320 --> 01:02:47.719
And that way you have kind of the,

01:02:47.719 --> 01:02:50.080
like you have like the most options, right?

01:02:50.080 --> 01:02:52.600
You could do it, you could put it on a website,

01:02:52.600 --> 01:02:55.080
you can put it on shinyapps.io

01:02:55.080 --> 01:02:56.679
or whatever it is that you need.

01:02:57.679 --> 01:02:59.000
Thank you very much.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:02:59.840
Thank you.

01:03:02.679 --> 01:03:04.280
Yeah, thank you, Isabella.

01:03:04.280 --> 01:03:08.280
Zarifa, yeah, I think everyone said it right.

01:03:08.280 --> 01:03:11.840
Would you like to ask Isabella directly your question?

01:03:12.879 --> 01:03:15.840
Sure, thank you, Isabella, for the presentation.

01:03:15.840 --> 01:03:17.479
It was really helpful.

01:03:17.479 --> 01:03:21.280
One question I have is I work with sensitive data a lot

01:03:21.280 --> 01:03:24.679
and we do make dashboards and want to make like, you know,

01:03:24.679 --> 01:03:27.600
if Shiny live is not the appropriate thing

01:03:27.600 --> 01:03:29.959
to work with sensitive data,

01:03:29.959 --> 01:03:33.760
what other servers do you suggest to use?

01:03:33.760 --> 01:03:36.800
When like we have audiences,

01:03:36.800 --> 01:03:39.919
outside audiences who wants to look into the dashboard,

01:03:39.919 --> 01:03:44.199
we don't want them to have the access to any sort of data.

01:03:44.199 --> 01:03:45.840
What do you suggest?

01:03:45.840 --> 01:03:47.239
Yeah, so I would say,

01:03:47.239 --> 01:03:48.959
I would suggest the ones that are listed

01:03:48.959 --> 01:03:52.479
in the traditional Shiny architecture page,

01:03:52.479 --> 01:03:55.399
like the, if you want on-prem,

01:03:55.399 --> 01:03:58.280
you can spin up your own RStudio server.

01:03:58.280 --> 01:04:00.479
If it's an enterprise solution,

01:04:00.479 --> 01:04:03.479
and my company Posit has one that like,

01:04:03.479 --> 01:04:06.479
it puts everything like behind the firewall.

01:04:06.479 --> 01:04:09.280
So Posit doesn't have access to the data,

01:04:09.280 --> 01:04:13.080
only you do, but all the apps are being hosted and,

01:04:13.080 --> 01:04:15.959
you know, secure and have the computation

01:04:15.959 --> 01:04:18.080
that they need to run and things like that.

01:04:18.080 --> 01:04:20.479
If it is something that say,

01:04:20.479 --> 01:04:23.120
like the problem with the cloud-based ones is right,

01:04:23.120 --> 01:04:25.320
like you're still giving,

01:04:25.320 --> 01:04:28.479
you're uploading your data to something else.

01:04:28.479 --> 01:04:31.360
And so if it is very sensitive data,

01:04:31.360 --> 01:04:35.080
I would say like it has to be kind of an on-prem solution.

01:04:35.080 --> 01:04:37.479
And then Shiny live is definitely not the right one

01:04:37.479 --> 01:04:41.360
because again, literally everything is sent

01:04:41.360 --> 01:04:43.520
when you share a Shiny live application.

01:04:43.520 --> 01:04:44.520
Yeah, thank you.

01:04:44.520 --> 01:04:47.520
Usually like the data sets are smaller.

01:04:47.520 --> 01:04:49.520
So, you know, we are always like confused,

01:04:49.520 --> 01:04:51.919
like what to go for, like, you know,

01:04:51.919 --> 01:04:54.520
buying something like more cloud-based

01:04:54.520 --> 01:04:58.919
are always not an option for us with student data.

01:04:58.919 --> 01:05:00.120
So always very confused.

01:05:00.120 --> 01:05:02.320
Sometimes we do use like Tableau,

01:05:02.320 --> 01:05:06.520
but again, like you cannot use outputs very easily

01:05:06.520 --> 01:05:09.520
as you can do with shinyapps.io.

01:05:09.520 --> 01:05:12.520
But, you know, very confusing, but thank you.

01:05:12.520 --> 01:05:13.520
Yeah.

01:05:13.520 --> 01:05:16.520
Another option of like on-prem, you know,

01:05:16.520 --> 01:05:18.520
generally at an organization like IT,

01:05:18.520 --> 01:05:21.520
you need to set the server and everything like that.

01:05:21.520 --> 01:05:24.520
One other kind of solution that I've seen

01:05:24.520 --> 01:05:28.520
is you build like the app itself

01:05:28.520 --> 01:05:31.520
and say you put data on shinyapps.io

01:05:31.520 --> 01:05:33.520
or PositConnect Cloud or something like that.

01:05:33.520 --> 01:05:36.520
But you can also use like a cloud-based solution

01:05:36.520 --> 01:05:38.520
like shinyapps.io or PositConnect Cloud

01:05:38.520 --> 01:05:39.520
or something like that,

01:05:39.520 --> 01:05:41.520
but you don't put the actual data.

01:05:41.520 --> 01:05:47.520
So in one of the examples in the Shiny Live documentation,

01:05:47.520 --> 01:05:52.520
it shows how to like upload a CSV, say, to a shiny app.

01:05:52.520 --> 01:05:55.520
So you kind of build the structure of a shiny app

01:05:55.520 --> 01:05:57.520
and then the plot that it would produce,

01:05:57.520 --> 01:05:58.520
say, from the data,

01:05:58.520 --> 01:06:00.520
but you don't actually put the data

01:06:00.520 --> 01:06:02.520
and then you share that app

01:06:02.520 --> 01:06:04.520
and then people upload their own data,

01:06:04.520 --> 01:06:05.520
you know, whenever they need to use it.

01:06:05.520 --> 01:06:07.520
But I would say like the issue with that is like

01:06:07.520 --> 01:06:09.520
it's not very scalable.

01:06:09.520 --> 01:06:12.520
The dataset has to be formatted correctly.

01:06:12.520 --> 01:06:16.520
Like so there are a lot of like kind of roadblocks

01:06:16.520 --> 01:06:18.520
that could happen if you try to share it that way.

01:06:18.520 --> 01:06:20.520
And so something that's on-prem

01:06:20.520 --> 01:06:25.520
is probably, you know, worth it to investigate and set up.

01:06:25.520 --> 01:06:27.520
Oh, I haven't thought about it.

01:06:27.520 --> 01:06:28.520
Thank you so much.

01:06:28.520 --> 01:06:33.520
Thank you.

01:06:33.520 --> 01:06:34.520
Great.

